# StudyBuddy Q backend — example environment
# Copy to backend/.env and fill in real values for local dev.
# NEVER commit a real .env file.

APP_ENV=development
LOG_LEVEL=INFO

# Redis — used for BYOK envelope storage and (later) Celery broker.
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379/0

# BYOK master key — 64 hex characters (32 bytes).
# Generate with: python -c "import os; print(os.urandom(32).hex())"
# This is a server-side master from which per-job keys are derived (HKDF).
# It does NOT decrypt anything by itself — see ADR-001.
BYOK_MASTER_KEY=replace_me_with_64_hex_chars_replace_me_with_64_hex_chars_replace_me

# System-owner (super-admin) secret — 64 hex characters (32 bytes). See ADR-018.
# Authenticates owner-only actions (publishing a book into the default library,
# vault ops). Required at startup — the backend fails fast if unset.
# Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32
SYSTEM_OWNER_SECRET=replace_me_with_64_hex_chars_replace_me_with_64_hex_chars_replace
# Stable, non-secret owner identifier (publisher of record + audit actor).
# SYSTEM_OWNER_ID=mentible-system-owner

# Default Anthropic model used when the request body omits it.
ANTHROPIC_DEFAULT_MODEL=claude-sonnet-4-6

# User identity (ADR-014 D1) — external IdP verified by JWKS. OPTIONAL: leave
# OIDC_ISSUER unset for the anonymous demo (auth is off; no startup failure).
# Supabase (O1): issuer is your project's auth URL; audience defaults to
# "authenticated"; JWKS is discovered at <issuer>/.well-known/jwks.json.
# OIDC_ISSUER=https://<project-ref>.supabase.co/auth/v1
# OIDC_AUDIENCE=authenticated
# OIDC_JWKS_URL=   # override only if not <issuer>/.well-known/jwks.json

# Supabase service-role key — HIGH-PRIVILEGE secret (full bypass of RLS + auth
# admin). Two consumers:
#   1. scripts/reset_test_user.py — delete a Supabase auth identity by email so a
#      test email can re-register from scratch (maintenance, out-of-band).
#   2. The RUNNING APP, when set, enables hard-deletion of the Supabase auth
#      identity on account/admin delete (ADR-022), so a deleted email re-registers
#      as a new user. UNSET ⇒ identity deletion is OFF and delete purges only the
#      app DB row (the pre-ADR-022 behavior) — graceful, no startup failure.
# This reverses ADR-014's "no service-role secret in the app runtime" for the
# deletion path only; set it deliberately, per environment, and never commit it.
# It is redacted from logs (ADR-001) and never persisted. Find it at Supabase →
# Project Settings → API → service_role (secret).
# SUPABASE_URL is optional; if unset it's derived from OIDC_ISSUER.
# SUPABASE_URL=https://<project-ref>.supabase.co
# SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=<service_role secret — do NOT commit>

# Super-admin operator role (ADR-020 D1). Comma-separated allowlist of VERIFIED
# IdP identities that get the /api/v1/admin/* console. Empty/unset ⇒ NO admins.
# Email is matched case-insensitively against the verified `email` claim; sub is
# for stability if an email changes. This is the human OPERATOR role — distinct
# from SYSTEM_OWNER_SECRET above, which is a signing capability (ADR-020 D4).
# SUPER_ADMIN_EMAILS=you@example.com,ops@example.com
# SUPER_ADMIN_SUBS=

# Managed billing (ADR-005 D6; MANAGED_BILLING_BUILD_PLAN.md, Phase 1). OPTIONAL —
# leave unset and the managed path is simply OFF (everyone uses BYOK). MANAGED_*_API_KEY
# is OUR company provider key (the "vault", option A); treated with the same no-log
# discipline as BYOK_MASTER_KEY — never commit a real value. Phase 1 is Anthropic-only.
# MANAGED_PLAN_EMAILS/SUBS is the internal staff allowlist that may use the managed path
# before plans/billing exist (comma-separated; empty ⇒ nobody is managed-eligible).
# MANAGED_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<our managed Anthropic key — do NOT commit>
# MANAGED_PLAN_EMAILS=you@example.com
# MANAGED_PLAN_SUBS=

# Account store (ADR-014 D2/D8) — Supabase Postgres via asyncpg. OPTIONAL: leave
# unset for the anonymous demo (no DB; account routes unavailable).
# ⚠️ Use the SESSION POOLER (port 5432), NOT:
#   - the direct host db.<ref>.supabase.co — it's IPv6-only, so it fails inside Docker
#     (it works from an IPv6-capable host, e.g. for running migrations locally);
#   - the transaction pooler (port 6543) — breaks asyncpg's prepared statements.
# Copy the exact host from Supabase → Connect → Session pooler (the aws-N-<region>
# prefix is project-specific and unguessable). User is postgres.<ref>. URL-encode any
# special chars in the password (e.g. @ → %40), or just use an alphanumeric password.
# Migrations: `cd backend && DATABASE_URL=... alembic upgrade head`.
# DATABASE_URL=postgresql://postgres.<project-ref>:<DB-PASSWORD>@aws-0-<region>.pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres
